//axhob_operation
{bust_invigilate_windows}

NOTE: The {busn_invigilate} ceremony on Windows — read-only host posture
verification. Asserts each posture fact matches its expected value; no
mutations, no remediation.

NOTE: Invocation contexts: {bust_caparison_windows} runs invigilate-windows
as its post-completion check; {bust_garrison_cygwin} and
{bust_garrison_wsl} run it as their precondition assertion before any
destructive workload work.

NOTE: Failure pointers discriminate operator-managed posture (→
{bust_handbook_windows}) from caparison-managed posture (→
{bust_caparison_windows}). PowerShell-side reads use
`Get-ItemPropertyValue`, `Get-Service`, `powercfg /a`, and `wsl.exe
--list --quiet`; bash-side BCG-compliant matching extracts each fact —
PowerShell stays out of the parsing business.

The {busn_invigilate} operation on Windows:

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{burp_investiture}

//axhoq_precondition
A {burp_regime} profile exists at the given {burp_investiture} and its
referenced {burn_regime} profile targets a Windows OpenSSH node
reachable as {burp_privileged_user} under key-only authentication using
{burp_privileged_key_file}. Invigilate does not establish that trust —
it presupposes it; admin SSH failure surfaces as the first posture
fact.

//axhos_step
. *Open admin SSH session*:
.. {busc_call}
ssh as {burp_privileged_user} using {burp_privileged_key_file};
key-auth only (no password fallback)
.. {busc_store}
`«ADMIN_SESSION»` for subsequent posture reads
.. {busc_fatal}
on connection failure with pointer to {bust_caparison_windows} —
admin trust is caparison-managed

//axhos_step
. *Assert operator-managed registry keys*:
.. For each {bust_handbook_windows}-established registry value
(canonical: `DevicePasswordLessBuildVersion` under
`HKLM\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\PasswordLess\Device`):
.. {busc_call}
PowerShell `Get-ItemPropertyValue` over `«ADMIN_SESSION»`
.. {busc_store}
`«REG_VALUE»` from the response
.. {busc_require}
{busc_use}
`«REG_VALUE»` matches the expected value
.. {busc_fatal}
on mismatch with pointer to {bust_handbook_windows} — these edits
are security-sensitive and operator-manual

//axhos_step
. *Assert AoAc override*:
.. {busc_call}
PowerShell `Get-ItemPropertyValue` for
`HKLM\System\CurrentControlSet\Control\Power\PlatformAoAcOverride`
.. {busc_store}
`«REG_AOAC»` from the response
.. {busc_require}
{busc_use}
`«REG_AOAC»` equals `0`
.. {busc_fatal}
on mismatch with pointer to {bust_handbook_windows} — Modern Standby
silently demotes `powercfg` operations until this override is in
place; it is a registry write requiring elevation, established once
by the operator

//axhos_step
. *Assert Tailscale service registered*:
.. {busc_call}
PowerShell `Get-Service Tailscale`
.. {busc_store}
`«SVC_TAILSCALE»` from the response
.. {busc_require}
{busc_use}
`«SVC_TAILSCALE»` is non-empty
.. {busc_fatal}
on absence with pointer to {bust_handbook_windows} — install +
Run-Unattended toggle + first auth are operator-manual

//axhos_step
. *Assert Tailscale service StartupType*:
.. {busc_call}
PowerShell `Get-Service Tailscale | Select-Object StartType`
.. {busc_store}
`«SVC_STARTTYPE»` from the response
.. {busc_require}
{busc_use}
`«SVC_STARTTYPE»` equals `Automatic`
.. {busc_fatal}
on mismatch with pointer to {bust_caparison_windows} — caparison
sets the StartupType after Tailscale is installed; non-Automatic
indicates caparison either did not run or its `Set-Service`
operation did not take

//axhos_step
. *Assert powercfg sleep/hibernate disabled*:
.. {busc_call}
`powercfg /a` over `«ADMIN_SESSION»`
.. {busc_store}
`«POWERCFG_REPORT»` from stdout
.. {busc_require}
{busc_use}
`«POWERCFG_REPORT»` reports neither standby nor hibernate as
available
.. {busc_fatal}
on mismatch with pointer to {bust_caparison_windows} — disabling
sleep and hibernate is caparison's phase-3 operation; a node still
advertising those states means caparison either did not run or its
`powercfg` calls were demoted to no-ops by a missing AoAc override

//axhos_step
. *Assert admin's rbtww-main WSL distribution registered*:
.. {busc_call}
`wsl.exe --list --quiet` over `«ADMIN_SESSION»`
.. {busc_store}
`«WSL_DISTRO_LIST»` from stdout
.. {busc_require}
{busc_use}
`«WSL_DISTRO_LIST»` contains `rbtww-main` (canonical name hardcoded
as `BUJB_wsl_distribution` in {bujb_jurisdiction})
.. {busc_fatal}
on absence with pointer to {bust_caparison_windows} — caparison's
phase-3 `wsl --import` from the Ubuntu-24.04 seed stages this
distribution; missing registration means caparison either did not
run or its import step failed without surfacing

//axhog_guarantee
On success:

* Every posture fact has been asserted to match its expected value.
* `«ADMIN_SESSION»` was used only for read commands.
* No remote or local mutation occurred.
* The node is in the shape {bust_caparison_windows} produces and
  {bust_garrison_cygwin} / {bust_garrison_wsl} require.

//axhoc_completion
Exit 0 when every posture fact matches its expected value.
Non-zero on the first mismatch, with a diagnostic naming the failing
fact, its expected value, its observed value, and the pointer
({bust_handbook_windows} for operator-managed facts;
{bust_caparison_windows} for caparison-managed facts).

input.content:
//axhob_operation
{bust_caparison_windows}

NOTE: The {busn_caparison} ceremony on Windows — three phases. Phase 1
establishes admin SSH key trust and hardens `sshd_config`. Phase 2
verifies the post-restart admin session authenticates by key alone.
Phase 3 applies post-trust admin posture: stages the `rbtww-main` WSL
distribution under the admin user, disables sleep and hibernate via
`powercfg`, and sets the Tailscale service to Automatic and running.
Closes with {bust_invigilate_windows} as the post-completion check.

NOTE: Nuclear: every invocation purges and re-establishes the
caparison-managed posture from scratch — no skip-if-present logic.
{bust_handbook_windows} owns security-sensitive operator-manual
posture; caparison owns the idempotent admin-shell remainder.

NOTE: Phase 1's `Restart-Service sshd` terminates its own ssh session
by design; the bash orchestrator treats the post-restart disconnect as
the expected phase boundary, not a failure. PowerShell-side
operations use `Get-Content`, `Set-Service`, `Start-Service`,
`Restart-Service`, and `wsl.exe --import`; bash-side BCG-compliant
matching extracts effective `sshd_config` directive values from the
raw bytes — PowerShell stays out of the parsing business.

The {busn_caparison} operation on Windows:

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{burp_investiture}

//axhoq_precondition
A {burp_regime} profile exists at the given {burp_investiture} and its
referenced {burn_regime} profile targets a Windows OpenSSH node.

//axhoq_precondition
{bust_handbook_windows} operator-manual scope is complete: OpenSSH
Server is installed and reachable, security-sensitive registry edits
have been applied (`DevicePasswordLessBuildVersion`,
`PlatformAoAcOverride`), Tailscale is installed with Run-Unattended
toggle set and first auth completed, netplwiz auto-login is
configured, and {burp_privileged_user} has a known password.
Caparison presupposes this scope, neither writes nor repairs it.

//axhoq_precondition
{burp_privileged_user} is a member of the Administrators group.

//axhoq_precondition
{burp_privileged_key_file} is unencrypted and exists on the operator's
station.

//axhos_step
. *Phase 1 — open admin SSH session*:
.. {busc_call}
ssh as {burp_privileged_user} with
`PreferredAuthentications=publickey,password`;
{burp_privileged_key_file} authenticates by key in steady state,
while the first run falls through to a TTY password prompt the
operator types once
.. {busc_store}
`«ADMIN_SESSION_P1»` for phase 1 operations
.. {busc_fatal}
on connection failure with pointer to {bust_handbook_windows} —
admin SSH reachability, the OpenSSH service running, the firewall
rule, and temporary `PasswordAuthentication yes` for first-run
fallback are handbook scope

//axhos_step
. *Phase 1 — derive admin pubkey*:
.. {busc_call}
`ssh-keygen -y` on {burp_privileged_key_file}
.. {busc_store}
`«ADMIN_PUBKEY»` from stdout
.. {busc_fatal}
on derivation failure — the privkey is encrypted (unsupported;
encrypted privkeys hang on the interactive passphrase prompt) or
unreadable

//axhos_step
. *Phase 1 — install admin pubkey*:
.. {busc_call}
write `«ADMIN_PUBKEY»` to `administrators_authorized_keys` over
`«ADMIN_SESSION_P1»` as a bare key entry — no `command=` directive.
Performed before any `sshd_config` change so key auth is available
for phase 2's reconnect. Nuclear: file replaced, not merged
.. {busc_fatal}
on write failure with pointer to {bust_handbook_windows} — the
operator-manual `PasswordAuthentication yes` must remain set so the
first-run admin SSH session can write the file before phase 1 flips
the directive back

//axhos_step
. *Phase 1 — lock down administrators_authorized_keys ACL*:
.. {busc_call}
`icacls` over `«ADMIN_SESSION_P1»` to restrict the ACL to SYSTEM and
the Administrators group; Windows OpenSSH refuses to read the file
otherwise. Idempotent
.. {busc_fatal}
on `icacls` failure — Windows OpenSSH will reject the
`administrators_authorized_keys` and admin SSH key auth will be
unreachable in phase 2

//axhos_step
. *Phase 1 — write hardened sshd_config directives*:
.. {busc_call}
write `PubkeyAuthentication yes`, `PasswordAuthentication no`, and
`PermitEmptyPasswords no` to `sshd_config` over `«ADMIN_SESSION_P1»`.
Idempotent — already-hardened configs converge to the same byte
sequence
.. {busc_fatal}
on write failure — `sshd_config` was not updated and a subsequent
restart would still serve password auth

//axhos_step
. *Phase 1 — verify hardened directives took*:
.. {busc_call}
PowerShell `Get-Content` on `sshd_config` over `«ADMIN_SESSION_P1»`
.. {busc_store}
`«SSHD_CONFIG_BYTES»` from the response
.. {busc_require}
{busc_use}
`«SSHD_CONFIG_BYTES»` parses (BCG-compliant matching) to
`PubkeyAuthentication yes`, `PasswordAuthentication no`, and
`PermitEmptyPasswords no` as the effective directive values
.. {busc_fatal}
on mismatch — the previous step's write did not take or a stale
override later in the file shadows the hardened directive

//axhos_step
. *Phase 1 — validate sshd_config*:
.. {busc_call}
`sshd -t` over `«ADMIN_SESSION_P1»` (penultimate atomic op of phase 1)
.. {busc_store}
`«SSHD_TEST_RESULT»` from the exit status
.. {busc_require}
{busc_use}
`«SSHD_TEST_RESULT»` is zero
.. {busc_fatal}
on non-zero — the hardened config is malformed; aborting before the
restart preserves the running sshd

//axhos_step
. *Phase 1 — restart sshd*:
.. {busc_call}
`Restart-Service sshd` over `«ADMIN_SESSION_P1»` (final atomic op of
phase 1)
.. {busc_fatal}
on restart-invocation failure other than the post-restart disconnect
— the disconnect itself is the expected phase boundary, not a
failure

//axhos_step
. *Phase 2 — reconnect under key-only auth*:
.. {busc_call}
ssh as {burp_privileged_user} with
`PreferredAuthentications=publickey` (no password fallback) using
{burp_privileged_key_file}
.. {busc_store}
`«ADMIN_SESSION_P2»` for phase 3 operations
.. {busc_fatal}
on reconnect failure — surfaces a brick: the operator's manual
password no longer opens a session, and the post-restart admin
session does not authenticate by key alone. Recovery is via the
operator's local console; {bust_invigilate_windows} would name the
failing posture fact in a subsequent diagnostic

//axhos_step
. *Phase 3 — stage rbtww-main WSL distribution*:
.. {busc_call}
`wsl.exe --import` from the Ubuntu-24.04 seed over
`«ADMIN_SESSION_P2»` to register the `rbtww-main` distribution under
the admin user. Canonical name hardcoded as `BUJB_wsl_distribution`
in {bujb_jurisdiction}. Nuclear: always purge-and-reimport
.. {busc_fatal}
on import failure — the WSL feature may be disabled, the seed
unavailable, or the admin user's HKCU\\Lxss state corrupted

//axhos_step
. *Phase 3 — disable powercfg sleep and hibernate*:
.. {busc_call}
`powercfg /change standby-timeout-ac 0`,
`powercfg /change standby-timeout-dc 0`, and
`powercfg /hibernate off` over `«ADMIN_SESSION_P2»`. Idempotent
.. {busc_fatal}
on `powercfg` failure with pointer to {bust_handbook_windows} — on
Modern Standby systems lacking the operator-managed
`PlatformAoAcOverride` registry write, these calls are silently
demoted to no-ops; the post-completion invigilate then surfaces the
unchanged powercfg report

//axhos_step
. *Phase 3 — set Tailscale service Automatic and running*:
.. {busc_call}
`Set-Service -Name Tailscale -StartupType Automatic` followed by
`Start-Service -Name Tailscale` over `«ADMIN_SESSION_P2»`. Idempotent
.. {busc_fatal}
on `Set-Service` or `Start-Service` failure with pointer to
{bust_handbook_windows} — Tailscale itself was installed,
Run-Unattended toggled, and first-auth completed by the operator;
caparison only sets the service shape

//axhos_step
. *Post-completion check — run invigilate-windows*:
.. {busc_call}
{bust_invigilate_windows} for this {burp_investiture}
.. {busc_store}
`«INVIGILATE_RESULT»` from its exit status and diagnostic
.. {busc_require}
{busc_use}
`«INVIGILATE_RESULT»` is zero
.. {busc_fatal}
on non-zero with the diagnostic surfaced verbatim — invigilate names
the failing posture fact and points the operator at either
{bust_handbook_windows} or {bust_caparison_windows}; this caparison
run cannot self-repair the failure

//axhog_guarantee
On success:

* Admin SSH is hardened to key-only with the operator's admin pubkey
  installed in `administrators_authorized_keys` under correct ACLs.
* `sshd_config` carries `PubkeyAuthentication yes`,
  `PasswordAuthentication no`, and `PermitEmptyPasswords no`.
* The post-restart admin session authenticates by key alone.
* The `rbtww-main` WSL distribution is registered under the admin user.
* `powercfg` sleep and hibernate are disabled.
* The Tailscale service is set to Automatic and running.
* {bust_invigilate_windows} has confirmed every posture fact end-to-end.

//axhoc_completion
Exit 0 when the post-completion {bust_invigilate_windows} passes.
Non-zero on phase-1 admin SSH failure, pubkey derivation or write
failure, ACL lockdown failure, `sshd_config` write or parse failure,
`sshd -t` failure, phase-2 key-auth reconnect failure, `wsl --import`
failure, `powercfg` failure, Tailscale service-shape failure, or
post-completion invigilate failure.

